\subsection{Switch Command}

The [[switch]] command is the user-facing realisation of the
context-switch design described in
\cref{sec:design-switch-functionality}.  It wraps the operations
stop-batch / push-stack / start-new into one atomic step, mirroring
the way an operating-system context switch saves and restores state.

We allow an optional [[-a]]/[[--all]] flag so the user can clear
\emph{all} active labels rather than just the most recent batch when
making the switch.  Timing options ([[--offset]], [[--at]]) are
supported for the same reason they exist on [[stop]] and [[start]]:
correcting mistakes after the fact.

<<switch command>>=
@cli.command()
def switch(
    labels: Optional[List[str]] = typer.Argument(
        None,
        help="Labels to switch to. "
             "If empty, switches back to saved labels.",
        autocompletion=complete_historical_labels),
    <<switch command options>>
):
    """
    Switch from the current labels to another context, with toggle support.

    Use this when work is interrupted by email, meetings, or a new task and you
    want one command to stop the old context and start the new one.

    \b
    Examples:
      nytid track switch email
      nytid track switch --all meeting
      nytid track switch --offset -15m DD1310
      nytid track switch
      nytid track switch --pop
      nytid track switch grading --pop
    """
    session = load_active_session(who)
    <<validate switch time options>>
    <<compute switch time>>
    if labels:
        <<switch to new labels>>
    else:
        <<switch back to saved labels>>
@

\subsubsection{Options}

When several unrelated batches are running simultaneously, it is
useful to get a clean slate before the switch rather than only
interrupting the most recent batch.  The [[-a]]/[[--all]] flag
provides this choice, mirroring the same option on [[stop]].

Timing options are needed because users often realise they should
have switched context some minutes ago---the [[--offset]] and [[--at]]
options allow backdating the moment of the switch so the recorded
durations remain accurate.

The [[--pop]] flag suppresses the save step.  Without it, stopped
labels are always stored as the \enquote{other} side of the toggle.
With it, the stopped labels are simply discarded.  When [[--pop]] is
used with explicit labels the new labels start without saving what was
running---useful for one-off interruptions you never want to return to.
When [[--pop]] is used without labels the toggle flips to the saved set
and then clears it, leaving only one active set in play.

<<switch command options>>=
    all_labels: bool = typer.Option(
        False, "--all", "-a",
        help="Stop all active labels, "
             "not just most recent batch"),
    pop: bool = typer.Option(
        False, "--pop", "-p",
        help="Do not save the stopped labels; "
             "discard the current context"),
    offset: Optional[str] = typer.Option(
        None, "--offset", "-o",
        help="Offset switch time "
             "(e.g., '-30m', '-1.5h', '30')"),
    at: Optional[str] = typer.Option(
        None, "--at",
        help="Switch at specific time "
             "(e.g., '14:30' or '2024-12-13 14:30')"),
    who: str = typer.Option(
        default_username, "--who", "-w",
        help="Worker identity (default: $USER)",
        autocompletion=complete_workers)
@

\subsubsection{Computing the Switch Time}

The same constraint that applies to [[stop]] and [[start]] applies
here: [[--offset]] and [[--at]] are mutually exclusive because they
express the same quantity (the moment of the switch) through
different representations.

<<validate switch time options>>=
if offset is not None and at is not None:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: Cannot use both --offset "
        "and --at options", err=True
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
@

<<compute switch time>>=
switch_time = datetime.datetime.now()
if at is not None:
    try:
        switch_time = parse_at_time(at)
    except ValueError as e:
        typer.echo(f"Error: {e}", err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(1)
elif offset is not None:
    try:
        switch_time += parse_offset(offset)
    except ValueError as e:
        typer.echo(
            f"Error parsing offset '{offset}': {e}",
            err=True
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
@

\subsubsection{Switching to New Labels}

The key question when labels are given is whether the current context
should be preserved for a later toggle.  By default it is: stopping
the current labels and storing them in [[switch_other]] keeps the two
contexts symmetric---a bare [[switch]] always returns you to where
you were.  With [[--pop]] you are declaring that the interrupted work
is disposable; [[switch_other]] is left unchanged so the toggle slot
is not polluted by a context you will never return to.

If nothing is active we still record an empty list (unless [[--pop]])
so a subsequent bare [[switch]] correctly restores the idle state.

<<switch to new labels>>=
if session.is_active():
    if all_labels:
        completed = session.stop_labels(
            count=len(session.label_order),
            end_time=switch_time, who=who)
    else:
        completed = session.stop_labels(
            end_time=switch_time,
            stop_batch=True, who=who)
    add_completed_entries(completed)
    for entry in completed:
        typer.echo(
            f"Stopped: "
            f"{get_labels_display(entry.labels)}"
            f" ({format_duration(entry.duration())})"
        )
    stopped_labels = [
        label
        for entry in completed
        for label in entry.labels
    ]
else:
    stopped_labels = []
if not pop:
    session.switch_other = stopped_labels
session.start_labels(labels, switch_time)
save_active_session(session, who)
typer.echo(f"Switched to: {', '.join(labels)}")
if at is not None or offset is not None:
    typer.echo(
        f"Switch time: "
        f"{switch_time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}"
    )
@

\subsubsection{Switching Back to Saved Labels}

Without labels we toggle: the saved set in [[switch_other]] becomes
active and the just-stopped labels become the new [[switch_other]]
---unless [[--pop]] was given, in which case [[switch_other]] is
cleared so there is nothing left to toggle back to.

If [[switch_other]] is [[None]] there is only one label set in play
and no toggle is possible.  We print an informational message and
exit cleanly rather than treating this as an error, because the user
may simply have forgotten they haven't set up a second context yet.

We stop the current labels first (honouring [[-a]]) so the time
between the forward switch and this reverse switch is recorded
properly before restoring the saved context.

<<switch back to saved labels>>=
if session.switch_other is None:
    typer.echo(
        "Nothing to switch back to: "
        "only one label set in play."
    )
    raise typer.Exit(0)
if session.is_active():
    if all_labels:
        completed = session.stop_labels(
            count=len(session.label_order),
            end_time=switch_time, who=who)
    else:
        completed = session.stop_labels(
            end_time=switch_time,
            stop_batch=True, who=who)
    add_completed_entries(completed)
    for entry in completed:
        typer.echo(
            f"Stopped: "
            f"{get_labels_display(entry.labels)}"
            f" ({format_duration(entry.duration())})"
        )
    stopped_labels = [
        label
        for entry in completed
        for label in entry.labels
    ]
else:
    stopped_labels = []
saved_labels = session.switch_other
if pop:
    session.switch_other = None
else:
    session.switch_other = stopped_labels
if saved_labels:
    session.start_labels(saved_labels, switch_time)
    typer.echo(
        f"Switched back to: "
        f"{', '.join(saved_labels)}"
    )
else:
    typer.echo(
        "Switched back "
        "(nothing was active before)"
    )
save_active_session(session, who)
if at is not None or offset is not None:
    typer.echo(
        f"Switch time: "
        f"{switch_time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}"
    )
@

